UNDIAGNOSED ILLNESS, TOXIC? - SUDAN (SOUTH) (02)
*********************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.healthnet.org/programs/promed.html>
See Also
Undiagnosed illness, toxic? - Sudan (south) 990818165329

Re: Mod.JW's comment in post above:
>The absence of fatalities suggests that a riot
> control agent may have been contained in the bombs. These
> agents are unfortunately not banned by international treaty.
[1
Date: Wed, 18 Aug 1999 14:36:58 -0700
From: ecroddy@miis.edu (Eric Croddy)

The probability that this could have been an incident involving riot
control agents (RCAs) is reasonably good, and the symptoms do
suggest those that can result from Adamsite and other arsenicals,
but includes also less toxic RCAs like CN and CS. However, NOx
off gases (sic), colored smokes, and fumes from white phosphorus-
type incendiaries are also relatively nasty in & of themselves, and
these are of course very conventional types of munitions.
RCAs are not allowed by the CWC [Chemical Weapons
Convention -- which the Sudan has recently joined -- to be used in
war, although the Sudan could possibly claim domestic use for
control of civilian disturbances. The U.S. reserves the right to use
RCAs in certain circumstances.
--
